EQUINE HERPES VIRUS AND STRANGLES - USA: (NEVADA) EQUINE
********************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Thu 23 Feb 2017
Source: News 4-Fox 11 [edited]
http://mynews4.com/news/local/state-officials-warn-of-horses-exposed-to-herpes-virus-bacterial-infection


State officials are warning that they have received reports of horses across Nevada that have been exposed to a herpes virus and a bacterial infection.

The Nevada Department of Agriculture said people have reported horses contracting equine herpesvirus type 4, or EHV-4, and _Streptococcus equi_ bacterial infection, also known as strangles or equine distemper.

Officials say these diseases are highly contagious among horses, and the state veterinarian has recommended postponing a high school rodeo in Moapa Valley this weekend [25-26 Feb 2017].

"Horses that were exposed last weekend [18-19 Feb 2017] may not exhibit clinical signs for several weeks, and we run the risk of exposing additional horses at the rodeo this weekend," Dr JJ Goicoechea said in a statement. "We may be issuing quarantine orders once confirmed. Our primary focus is stopping the spread and protecting our equine population."

Both EHV-4 and strangles affect the upper respiratory system in horses and can cause lifelong illness. Horse owners are advised to make sure vaccinations are current, and anyone who suspects a horse is exhibiting signs should contact a veterinarian and not let it come into contact with other horses.

State law requires any owner with knowledge of an infected animal to notify the state quarantine office.

